---

🔬 STEP 4: SQL INJECTION ANALYSIS MODEL

4.1 Identify INPUT SOURCES

- User inputs (forms, APIs, query params)
- Headers, cookies
- File input
- External APIs

---

4.2 Identify SQL SINKS

- Direct queries:
  - SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE
- Dynamic query construction
- Stored procedures
- ORM execution methods

---

4.3 Detect QUERY CONSTRUCTION PATTERNS

Flag:

- String concatenation
- String interpolation
- Dynamic query building
- Template-based SQL
- Unsafe query builders

---

4.4 SOURCE → QUERY TRACE (MANDATORY)

For EACH query:

- Trace:
  input → variable → query → execution

---

🧨 STEP 5: SQL INJECTION VARIANT COVERAGE

You MUST check ALL types:

---

5.1 Classic SQL Injection

- Direct concatenation into queries

---

5.2 Blind SQL Injection

- Boolean-based logic
- Time-based queries

---

5.3 Second-Order SQL Injection

- Stored input later used in queries

---

5.4 Stored Procedure Injection

- Unsafe parameter passing

---

5.5 ORM Injection

- Unsafe query builder usage
- Raw queries inside ORM

---

5.6 NoSQL Injection (if applicable)

- MongoDB-style queries
- JSON-based injections

---

5.7 Union-Based Injection

- UNION SELECT misuse

---

5.8 Error-Based Injection

- Database error exposure

---

5.9 Out-of-Band Injection

- External callbacks (DNS/HTTP)

---

🛡️ STEP 6: MITIGATION VALIDATION (MANDATORY)

For EACH query verify:

SAFE CONTROLS:

- Parameterized queries / prepared statements
- ORM safe bindings
- Stored procedures (safe usage)
- Input validation (strict, not blacklist)

---

UNSAFE CONTROLS:

- Manual sanitization only
- Regex filtering only
- Escaping without parameterization

---

DECISION:

- Proper parameterization → Protected
- Weak/incorrect control → Vulnerable
- Cannot verify → Not Confirmed

---

🔄 STEP 7: CROSS-FILE ANALYSIS

- Track input defined in one file and used in another
- Validate multi-step query construction

